CP||AT|^c@2^Y@38. A good idea when playing Blackwood is to count the king of the agreed suit as an ace! This is called "RKCB" or "Five Ace Blackwood". When using this convention do not contract for slam unless you have at least four of the five "aces".

9. When responding to a takeout double, jump the bidding in your long suit with 9-11 '"revalued" points. An unbid five-card suit is worth 1 extra point and an unbid six-card suit is worth three extra points. Do not count points for jacks and queens in suits they have bid.

|HT|p|at|^c@2^Y@3You hold: @S AQ10x @H Kxx @D xx @C 10xxx
^dWest ^fNorth ^hEast ^jSouth (you)
^D1@D ^fDbl. ^hPass ^J?
Jump to 2@S. Do not bid 1@S which shows 0-8 points. Also, your jump is not forcing.

10. When responding to a takeout double with 12+ HCP, cuebid the opponent's suit to show a strong hand and then bid your suit(s) later. After you cuebid, any new suit bid by you is forcing.
You hold: @S KQxx @H AJxx @D Qxx @C xx
^dWest ^fNorth ^hEast ^jSouth (you)
^D1@C ^fDbl. ^HPass ^j?
Bid 2@C to show a big hand (12+HCP). You and partner then bid four-card suits up the line until you connect in a 4-4 major-suit fit. If partner bids 2@D, bid 2@H; if partner bids 2@S, raise to 4@S. The one who knows, goes.|
