^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|HCP showing steps are really a bad idea. As those who play Bergen hand evaluation know, HCP are only a small part of how you evaluate your hand. And knowing how many HCP responder has is usually not important to a 2@C opener, especially when they are opening it based on a long strong suit. Knowing how many aces and kings has some importance, so control showing steps have some merit.|
PG| ***** 120 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Showing controls have some big disadvantages in particular. They often get the bidding up too high too fast and they wrong side the contract sometimes. So I think the automatic 2@D response is the best way to go. That way the 2@C opener can then describe why he opened 2@C and the auction can proceed from there at the lowest possible level.|
PG| ***** 121 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Some people play 2@H shows a "bust" hand either no aces or kings or no more than 1 king and no aces. 2@H bust is ok, but that can also wrong side the contract. I prefer playing what is known as "3@C second nagtive". If it goes:|cs|6|

HT|l|at|^B{|ia|,2cp2dp2hp3c|at|}|ht|m|at|^mor|HT|l|at|^n{|ia|,2cp2dp2sp3c|at|}|
ht|q|at|^B@2The 3@C bid shows the bust hand. That is sometimes called "3@C - 2nd negative". That lets opener describe their hand and still lets responder show a bust hand over 2 of a major. Over a 2N rebid there is no reason to show a bust.

Generally, I try not to open 2@C and rebid 3@C or 3@D, but if I do then you just lose the ability for responder to show a bust hand.|
